</div>
<div id="c7">
<p>It sounds like you came up with this on your own (kudos), but this is a well known concept called customer lifetime value.</p>

<p>No one analyzing Groupon&#8217;s filing misunderstood the concept of lifetime value. The tricky part isn&#8217;t understanding the concept that securing a stream of payments in the future is worth paying for, the tricky part is modelling what those payments are going to be and how much they are worth today.</p>

<p>ASCOI implies a level of profitability which is achievable with zero marketing. The model underlying this is incredibly simplistic and almost certainly the wrong way to look at their customer lifetime value.</p>

<p class="posted">posted by Adam
 on August 18, 2011 <a href="acsoi#c7" rel="bookmark">#</a></p>
</div>
<div id="c8">
<p>I think the problem with your allegory is that your customers actually get a box of cereal every week.  Groupon actually doesn&#8217;t deliver anything of direct tangible value to the consumer.  I could sign up and NEVER get any benefit because I don&#8217;t like any of the stuff they&#8217;re hawking.</p>

<p>A slightly different perspective can be found on my <a href="http://mikemainguy.blogspot.com/2011/08/groupon-makes-me-tired.html" rel="nofollow">blog</a></p>

